    </div>

    <h3>Convergence: the epsilon-N definition</h3>
    <p>A sequence (a_n) <strong>converges</strong> to L if for every &epsilon; &gt; 0, there exists N such that for all n &ge; N, |a_n - L| &lt; &epsilon;. The key: you pick any &epsilon;, no matter how small, and I produce an N that works.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Sequence a_n = 1/n converges to 0
; For any epsilon, find N such that 1/n < epsilon for all n >= N

(define (find-N epsilon)
  (let loop ((n 1))
    (if (< (/ 1.0 n) epsilon) n (loop (+ n 1)))))

(display "epsilon = 0.1, N = ")
(display (find-N 0.1)) (newline)
(display "epsilon = 0.01, N = ")
(display (find-N 0.01)) (newline)
(display "epsilon = 0.001, N = ")
(display (find-N 0.001)) (newline)

; Verify: all terms past N are within epsilon
(define (verify-convergence epsilon)
  (let* ((N (find-N epsilon))
         (checks (list N (+ N 1) (+ N 5) (+ N 50))))
    (for-each (lambda (n)
      (display "  a_")
      (display n)
      (display " = ")
      (display (/ 1.0 n))
      (display (if (< (/ 1.0 n) epsilon) " < epsilon" " >= epsilon"))
      (newline))
    checks)))

(display "Checking epsilon = 0.05:") (newline)
(verify-convergence 0.05)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Convergence of 1/n to 0
import math

def find_N(epsilon):
    return math.ceil(1 / epsilon)

for eps in [0.1, 0.01, 0.001]:
    N = find_N(eps)
    print(f"eps={eps}, N={N}, a_N={1/N:.6f} < {eps}: {1/N < eps}")
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Limit theorems</h3>
    <p>Limits respect arithmetic: if a_n &rarr; a and b_n &rarr; b, then a_n + b_n &rarr; a + b, a_n * b_n &rarr; a * b, and (if b &ne; 0) a_n / b_n &rarr; a / b. The squeeze theorem: if a_n &le; c_n &le; b_n and both a_n and b_n converge to L, then c_n &rarr; L.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Limit theorems: sum, product, squeeze
; a_n = 1 + 1/n -> 1
; b_n = 2 - 1/n -> 2

(define (a n) (+ 1 (/ 1.0 n)))
(define (b n) (- 2 (/ 1.0 n)))

(display "Sum: a_n + b_n -> 1 + 2 = 3") (newline)
(display "  n=100: ")
(display (+ (a 100) (b 100))) (newline)

(display "Product: a_n * b_n -> 1 * 2 = 2") (newline)
(display "  n=100: ")
(display (* (a 100) (b 100))) (newline)

; Squeeze: -1/n <= sin(n)/n <= 1/n, both bounds -> 0
(display "Squeeze: |sin(n)/n| <= 1/n -> 0") (newline)
(display "  sin(100)/100 = ")
(display (/ (sin 100) 100)) (newline)
(display "  1/100         = ")
(display (/ 1.0 100))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Python equivalent
import math

a = lambda n: 1 + 1/n
b = lambda n: 2 - 1/n

print("Sum: a_n + b_n -> 3")
print("  n=100:", a(100) + b(100))
print("Product: a_n * b_n -> 2")
print("  n=100:", a(100) * b(100))
print("Squeeze: |sin(n)/n| <= 1/n -> 0")
print("  sin(100)/100 =", math.sin(100)/100)
print("  1/100         =", 1/100)
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Monotone convergence theorem</h3>
    <p>Every bounded, monotone sequence converges. If a sequence is increasing and bounded above, it converges to its supremum. This is a direct consequence of the completeness axiom.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Monotone convergence: a_n = sum_{k=1}^{n} 1/k!
; Increasing and bounded above by 3, converges to e

(define (factorial n)
  (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))

(define (partial-e n)
  (let loop ((k 0) (sum 0.0))
    (if (> k n) sum
      (loop (+ k 1) (+ sum (/ 1.0 (factorial k)))))))

(display "Partial sums of 1/k! (converging to e):") (newline)
(for-each (lambda (n)
  (display "  n=")
  (display n)
  (display ": ")
  (display (partial-e n))
  (newline))
  (list 1 2 5 10 15))

(display "Bounded above by 3? ")
(display (< (partial-e 15) 3))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Python equivalent
import math

def partial_e(n):
    return sum(1/math.factorial(k) for k in range(n + 1))

print("Partial sums of 1/k! (converging to e):")
for n in [1, 2, 5, 10, 15]:
    print("  n=" + str(n) + ":", partial_e(n))

print("Bounded above by 3?", partial_e(15) < 3)
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem</h3>
    <p>Every bounded sequence has a convergent subsequence. This is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolzano%E2%80%93Weierstrass_theorem"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem</a>, the key compactness result for sequences. Even if a sequence doesn't converge (like (-1)^n), some subsequence does.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Bolzano-Weierstrass: bounded sequence has convergent subsequence
; a_n = (-1)^n * (1 + 1/n) does not converge
; but the subsequence a_{2k} = 1 + 1/(2k) -> 1

(define (a n)
  (* (if (even? n) 1 -1)
     (+ 1 (/ 1.0 n))))

(display "Full sequence (diverges):") (newline)
(for-each (lambda (n)
  (display "  a_")
  (display n)
  (display " = ")
  (display (a n))
  (newline))
  (list 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8))

(display "Even subsequence (converges to 1):") (newline)
(for-each (lambda (k)
  (let ((n (* 2 k)))
    (display "  a_")
    (display n)
    (display " = ")
    (display (a n))
    (newline)))
  (list 1 2 5 10 50 100))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Python equivalent
a = lambda n: (1 if n % 2 == 0 else -1) * (1 + 1/n)

print("Full sequence (diverges):")
for n in range(1, 9):
    print("  a_" + str(n) + " =", a(n))

print("Even subsequence (converges to 1):")
for k in [1, 2, 5, 10, 50, 100]:
    n = 2 * k
    print("  a_" + str(n) + " =", a(n))
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Cauchy sequences</h3>
    <p>A sequence is <strong>Cauchy</strong> if its terms get arbitrarily close to each other: for every &epsilon;, there exists N such that |a_m - a_n| &lt; &epsilon; for all m, n &ge; N. In the reals, a sequence converges if and only if it is Cauchy. This equivalence is another way to state completeness.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Cauchy criterion: terms get close to each other
; a_n = sum_{k=1}^{n} 1/k^2 is Cauchy (converges to pi^2/6)

(define (partial-sum n)
  (let loop ((k 1) (s 0.0))
    (if (> k n) s
      (loop (+ k 1) (+ s (/ 1.0 (* k k)))))))

; Check Cauchy: |a_m - a_n| for large m, n
(display "Cauchy check for sum 1/k^2:") (newline)
(let* ((a100 (partial-sum 100))
       (a200 (partial-sum 200))
       (a500 (partial-sum 500))
       (a1000 (partial-sum 1000)))
  (display "  |a_200 - a_100| = ")
  (display (abs (- a200 a100))) (newline)
  (display "  |a_500 - a_200| = ")
  (display (abs (- a500 a200))) (newline)
  (display "  |a_1000 - a_500| = ")
  (display (abs (- a1000 a500))) (newline)
  (display "  a_1000 = ")
  (display a1000) (newline)
  (display "  pi^2/6 = ")
  (display (/ (* 3.141592653589793 3.141592653589793) 6.0)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Python equivalent
import math

def partial_sum(n):
    return sum(1/(k*k) for k in range(1, n + 1))

a100 = partial_sum(100)
a200 = partial_sum(200)
a500 = partial_sum(500)
a1000 = partial_sum(1000)

print("Cauchy check for sum 1/k^2:")
print("  |a_200 - a_100| =", abs(a200 - a100))
print("  |a_500 - a_200| =", abs(a500 - a200))
print("  |a_1000 - a_500| =", abs(a1000 - a500))
print("  a_1000 =", a1000)
print("  pi^2/6 =", math.pi**2 / 6)
`} />
    </div>

